{
  "doc_id": "47773",
  "text": "In the study of solid renal masses, the role for US has been mainly centred on the differentiation of RCC and AML, which are the most common malignant and benign solid renal tumors, respectively [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . When a solid mass is diagnosed, RCC or AML should be initially considered because of the high frequency of their occurrence. At US, most AML lesions are markedly hyperechoic relative to renal parenchyma. They may appear less echogenic depending on the relative proportion of fat, smooth muscle, vascular components, and haemorrhage in the lesion [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . RCC displays a broad range of echogenicities. Although often thought of as hypoechoic or isoechoic, recent studies have shown that most RCC are hyperechoic relative to renal parenchyma and that up to 12% simulate AML [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Forman et al. [CITATION_11] have shown that one third of small RCC are as echogenic as a \"classical\" AML. An echotexture equal to that of renal sinus fat seen in a small renal mass is, therefore, no longer considered adequate to exclude the diagnosis of malignancy (see Figure 3) .",
